I use a pretty blue glass pen for more formal correspondence. It'll accept inks with gold flecks, which most fountain pens won't (they clog), so my go-to ink is an indigo with a fine gold fleck that shows beautifully in bright light.


I'd think those would work well in some drawings as well, where you couldn't easily add that accent with a standard pen.

snippet.textDisplay:
I use these glass pens mainly for calligraphy, the one you have is quite a cheap one and there are some of better quality ones out there that I feel don't scratch up the paper as much. Swapping inks is a breeze and the line thickness is consistent and well-defined, suitable for certain styles of calligraphy.
Many people who use these use them with fountain pen inks as well, so I think you can get document inks that won't bleed if you give sufficient drying time, but most of the people who use these for sketching that I know of, use them for free hand drawing.
snippet.textOriginal:

snippet.textDisplay:
Dip pens aren't necessarily meant to compare to drawing pens, most have varied nibs so you can get different line variations.
Dip pens allow for varied line work, due to amount of ink, how the pen is held, and of course practice.
I recently got a glass version, which doesn't have the same exact experience as using a traditional dip, but it relatively smooth and like Jazza showed, it really holds the ink.
The issue that Jazza is probably having to wrong ink choice.
With this sort of pen I would strictly use any variety of India ink. The ink provided (similar to what came with mine) is watery and has a similar spread and absorption as something like a highlighter would have.
India ink is water friendly for diluting, making the ink lighter, but is also just more pigmented and pretty close to marker ink. Just no felt tips which can provide their own texture...
I'm a fan of both, but if a project needs grit and texture, dip pens are my go to. For something that needs to be stream line like illustration, like most of Jazza's work is, markers are easier.
That's where the glass pen fits in, it's a cool balance between the two.
Fragile as the are, they can create that varied and gritty look, but can give smoothness when you want.
Idk. That's just me. I love all three but for totally different reasons.
